### Tool Class — `ApiTools.cs`

```csharp
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;

[McpServerToolType]
public class ApiTools(HttpClient httpClient, ILogger<ApiTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Fetch a user by ID from the REST API.")]
    public async Task<string> GetUser(
        [Description("The numeric user ID")] int userId,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching user {UserId}", userId);
        var json = await httpClient.GetStringAsync(
            $"https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users/{userId}", cancellationToken);
        return json;
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("List all posts, optionally filtered by user ID.")]
    public async Task<string> ListPosts(
        [Description("Filter posts to this user ID (optional)")] int? userId = null,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var url = userId.HasValue
            ? $"https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts?userId={userId}"
            : "https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts";

        logger.LogInformation("Listing posts (userId={UserId})", userId);
        var json = await httpClient.GetStringAsync(url, cancellationToken);
        return json;
    }
}
```

### `Program.cs` — stdio transport

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: log to stderr only — stdout is the JSON-RPC protocol channel
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

builder.Services.AddHttpClient();  // registers IHttpClientFactory + HttpClient

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

---

### How DI works for MCP tools

The SDK supports **two injection styles**:

| Style | How it works |
|---|---|
| **Constructor injection** (non-static class) | Services like `HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>` are injected via the primary constructor. The class is instantiated per-request by the DI container. |
| **Method parameter injection** (static class) | DI services appear as method parameters and are resolved automatically. |

**Key rule:** The SDK distinguishes DI services from tool parameters by type. `HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`, `CancellationToken`, `IMcpServer`, and `IProgress<T>` are **never** exposed in the tool schema — they're injected silently. Only parameters with `[Description]` attributes appear in the schema the LLM sees.

In the example above, `ApiTools` uses **constructor injection** — `HttpClient` and `ILogger<ApiTools>` come from `builder.Services.AddHttpClient()` and the built-in logging, respectively. The LLM only sees `userId` and `userId?` as callable parameters.
